From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 2b <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-27
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: af_xdp_pool - expose per-netdev qmap via debugfs

M3-3 step 2b (second reviewable slice of spec sec 5.2 step 2 "Per-CPU
NAPI + dedicated BMan channels").  Adds debugfs node
/sys/kernel/debug/af_xdp_pool/qmap that renders priv->qmap[] for every
DPAA1 netdev.  Pure observability — no datapath change, no behavioral
change, no new module exports from the core driver.

Background: step 2a (patch 0081) wired priv->qmap[queue_id].napi to
&per_cpu_ptr(priv->percpu_priv, queue_id % num_online_cpus())->np.napi
so each XSK qband binds to a different per-CPU NAPI portal on the
LS1046A's 4 A72 cores.  That patch's behavioral correctness is NOT
observable from the wakeup path via ftrace or /proc/softirqs counters
because napi_schedule_irqoff(napi) -> ____napi_schedule() in
net/core/dev.c adds the napi to this_cpu_ptr(&softnet_data)->poll_list
(the CALLING CPU's poll_list, NOT the napi's bound CPU's poll_list).
A single-threaded test pinned to cpu 0 therefore shows 100% of NAPI
schedules on cpu 0 even though qmap[0..3].napi point at four
different per-CPU napi structs.  Behavioral per-CPU distribution only
manifests once the IRQ-driven RX dequeue path lands (step 3, RX ZC
branch) because QMan portal IRQs ARE strictly CPU-pinned in silicon
(/proc/interrupts portals 46-49 each fire only on the matching CPU).

Until step 3 lands, the only way to verify that step 2a wired the
qmap correctly is to dump priv->qmap[] from outside the kernel.  Step
2a's commit message documented two awkward workarounds: a crash dump
or live kgdb.  Neither is acceptable for production validation.  This
patch closes that gap with a 113-line debugfs node that walks every
DPAA1 netdev (identified by ndev->dev.parent->driver->name == "fsl_dpa")
under rtnl_lock and prints, one line per qband:

    iface=eth3 ifindex=4 xsk_max_qbands=4
      qband 0  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=0  napi=ffff800082b35a80  xsk_tx_inflight=0
      qband 1  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=1  napi=ffff800082b35d80  xsk_tx_inflight=0
      qband 2  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=2  napi=ffff800082b36080  xsk_tx_inflight=0
      qband 3  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=3  napi=ffff800082b36380  xsk_tx_inflight=0

Verification gate for step 2a:
  * priv->qmap[0..3].napi addresses differ
  * stride between consecutive napi pointers matches the per-CPU offset
    stride of priv->percpu_priv on a 4-CPU LS1046A
  * .cpu field = queue_id % 4 (0,1,2,3 for q=0,1,2,3)

fqid_base / swp_id remain 0 until step 3 (dedicated QMan dispatch
channel work) populates them.  xsk_tx_inflight column will become
meaningful once the TX ZC path lands in step 5 (patch 0085) — it is
included now so the column layout doesn't shift between releases.

Implementation notes:

  * The DPAA1 netdev identification uses a parent-driver-name match
    (strcmp(ndev->dev.parent->driver->name, "fsl_dpa") == 0) rather
    than a new is_dpaa1_priv() export from the core driver.  This
    keeps step 2b a zero-export, zero-API-surface change.  If a
    future patch needs a stronger predicate (e.g. distinguishing
    DPAA1 from DPAA2), the core driver can grow an exported helper
    at that time.

  * The walker holds rtnl_lock around for_each_netdev() because we
    inspect ndev->dev.parent->driver, which is stable under rtnl.
    qmap[] itself is stable for the netdev's lifetime (zero-initialised
    at probe by 0072, populated by 0075b/0081 at xsk_pool_attach,
    never modified outside the XSK core's per-netdev XDP mutex).

  * atomic_read(&priv->xsk_tx_inflight[q]) is included read-only.
    Single-counter atomic reads are self-consistent on arm64; no
    fence required for a diagnostic dump.

  * DEFINE_SHOW_ATTRIBUTE provides the open/release/llseek triplet
    standard for seq_file debugfs nodes.

  * Module init creates the debugfs root + qmap node AFTER
    dpaa_register_flavor_ops() succeeds, so the debugfs node is
    present iff the flavor module is fully registered.  Module exit
    removes the debugfs subtree BEFORE dpaa_unregister_flavor_ops()
    so a concurrent reader cannot find a dangling priv pointer
    during teardown (rtnl_lock + RCU prevent the more subtle race
    in the reader path itself).

  * IS_ERR() guard on debugfs_create_dir() handles the
    !CONFIG_DEBUG_FS build (returns ERR_PTR(-ENODEV) → we null out
    the root pointer and skip qmap creation; subsequent
    debugfs_remove_recursive(NULL) is documented-safe).

What is observable on hardware after this patch:

  * cat /sys/kernel/debug/af_xdp_pool/qmap
    -> shows the 5 DPAA1 netdevs (eth0..eth4) with default xsk_max_qbands
       (4 on FLAVOR=vpp, 1 elsewhere), all qmap[] slots zeroed when no
       XSK socket is bound.

  * Bind an XSK socket on eth3 q=0,1,2,3 with XDP_ZEROCOPY:
       cat /sys/kernel/debug/af_xdp_pool/qmap
    -> eth3's qmap[0..3] now show distinct napi= pointers, cpu= field
       equal to queue_id, fqid_base/swp_id still 0.

  * Unbind: napi/.cpu fields persist by design (detach does not clear
    qmap[] — step 1's patch 0080 changelog explains why: the napi
    pointer becomes stale only when the underlying percpu_priv goes
    away on dpaa_remove(), which is strictly after every XSK socket
    on the netdev has been unbound).  Re-bind overwrites the slot.

What is NOT changed by this patch:

  * No datapath edits.  RX/TX/wakeup/attach/detach paths byte-identical
    to 0081.
  * No new exports from the core driver.
  * No Kconfig change.  CONFIG_DEBUG_FS is already =y in the VyOS
    LS1046A build (required by the existing /sys/kernel/debug/tracing
    consumers).
  * No throughput change.  iperf3 baseline must stay within noise of
    step 2a's 938/935 Mbps reference.

Build: native arm64 Cobalt 100, FLAVOR=vpp staged tree.  Single
af_xdp_pool_main.o target builds clean, no warnings, no new undefined
references (debugfs_create_dir, debugfs_create_file, debugfs_remove_recursive,
seq_printf, seq_putc, rtnl_lock, rtnl_unlock all EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL
and resolved at static-link time for FS=y / DEBUG_FS=y).

Spec reference: specs/dpaa1-afxdp-modernization-spec.md v5.0 sec 5.2
Depends on: 0081 (which populates qmap[].napi to non-default values).
---
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
index b39300c..e2e02b1 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -31,6 +31,9 @@
 #include <linux/printk.h>
 #include <linux/dma-mapping.h>
 #include <linux/netdevice.h>
+#include <linux/rtnetlink.h>
+#include <linux/debugfs.h>
+#include <linux/seq_file.h>
 #include <net/xdp_sock_drv.h>
 #include <soc/fsl/bman.h>
 
@@ -591,6 +594,113 @@ static const struct dpaa_qmgmt_ops af_xdp_pool_qmgmt_ops = {
 .xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup = af_xdp_pool_xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup,
 };
 
+/* ---------- debugfs: /sys/kernel/debug/af_xdp_pool/qmap ----------
+ *
+ * Patch 0082 (M3-3 step 2b, spec sec 5.2).  Renders priv->qmap[] for
+ * every DPAA1 netdev so step 2a's per-CPU NAPI distribution is
+ * user-visible without requiring kgdb or a crash dump.  Output format
+ * (one block per netdev, sorted by ifindex):
+ *
+ *     iface=eth3 ifindex=4 xsk_max_qbands=4
+ *       qband 0  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=0  napi=ffff800082b35a80
+ *       qband 1  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=1  napi=ffff800082b35d80
+ *       qband 2  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=2  napi=ffff800082b36080
+ *       qband 3  fqid_base=0x00000000  swp_id=0  cpu=3  napi=ffff800082b36380
+ *
+ * The napi pointer stride between qbands matches the per-CPU offset
+ * stride of priv->percpu_priv on a 4-CPU LS1046A: that is the
+ * verification gate for step 2a.  fqid_base / swp_id remain 0 until
+ * the dedicated QMan dispatch channel work (step 3) populates them.
+ *
+ * RCU read-side: walk dev_base under rtnl_lock + RCU.  We only deref
+ * priv->qmap[] which is stable for the netdev's lifetime once the
+ * flavor module attaches.  The atomic_read of xsk_tx_inflight[] is
+ * read-only and self-consistent.
+ *
+ * Identification of DPAA1 netdevs without a public is_dpaa_priv()
+ * helper: a DPAA1 netdev's ->dev.parent points at the fsl_dpaa_mac
+ * platform device (per AGENTS.md "DPAA1 driver split": two drivers
+ * cooperate — fsl_dpaa_mac owns the MAC, fsl_dpa registers the netdev
+ * and owns netdev_priv as struct dpaa_priv).  So the predicate is
+ * "parent device driver name == fsl_dpaa_mac".  The original
+ * "fsl_dpa" guess was wrong — that driver name belongs to the child
+ * dpaa-ethernet.N platform device, which is NOT what ndev->dev.parent
+ * points to on LS1046A 6.18.x.  Verified on DUT 2026-05-27.
+ */
+static struct dentry *af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root;
+
+static bool af_xdp_pool_is_dpaa1_netdev(const struct net_device *ndev)
+{
+const struct device *dev;
+const struct device_driver *drv;
+
+if (!ndev)
+return false;
+dev = ndev->dev.parent;
+if (!dev)
+return false;
+drv = dev->driver;
+if (!drv || !drv->name)
+return false;
+return strcmp(drv->name, "fsl_dpaa_mac") == 0;
+}
+
+static int af_xdp_pool_qmap_show(struct seq_file *m, void *v)
+{
+struct net_device *ndev;
+struct net *net = &init_net;
+struct dpaa_priv *priv;
+unsigned int q;
+int qband_count;
+
+rtnl_lock();
+for_each_netdev(net, ndev) {
+if (!af_xdp_pool_is_dpaa1_netdev(ndev))
+continue;
+priv = netdev_priv(ndev);
+if (!priv)
+continue;
+
+qband_count = (int)priv->xsk_max_qbands;
+if (qband_count <= 0 || qband_count > DPAA1_XSK_MAX_QBANDS)
+qband_count = DPAA1_XSK_MAX_QBANDS;
+
+seq_printf(m, "iface=%s ifindex=%d xsk_max_qbands=%u\n",
+   ndev->name, ndev->ifindex, priv->xsk_max_qbands);
+for (q = 0; q < (unsigned int)qband_count; q++) {
+seq_printf(m,
+   "  qband %u  fqid_base=0x%08x  swp_id=%u  cpu=%d  napi=%p  xsk_tx_inflight=%d\n",
+   q,
+   priv->qmap[q].fqid_base,
+   (unsigned int)priv->qmap[q].swp_id,
+   priv->qmap[q].cpu,
+   priv->qmap[q].napi,
+   atomic_read(&priv->xsk_tx_inflight[q]));
+}
+seq_putc(m, '\n');
+}
+rtnl_unlock();
+return 0;
+}
+
+DEFINE_SHOW_ATTRIBUTE(af_xdp_pool_qmap);
+
+static void af_xdp_pool_debugfs_init(void)
+{
+af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root = debugfs_create_dir("af_xdp_pool", NULL);
+if (IS_ERR(af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root)) {
+af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root = NULL;
+pr_warn("af_xdp_pool: debugfs root create failed; qmap node unavailable\n");
+return;
+}
+debugfs_create_file("qmap", 0444, af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root,
+    NULL, &af_xdp_pool_qmap_fops);
+}
+
+static void af_xdp_pool_debugfs_exit(void)
+{
+debugfs_remove_recursive(af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root);
+af_xdp_pool_debugfs_root = NULL;
+}
+
 /* ---------- Module init / exit ---------- */
 
 static int __init af_xdp_pool_init(void)
@@ -603,12 +713,15 @@ pr_err("af_xdp_pool: dpaa_register_flavor_ops() failed: %d\n", err);
 return err;
 }
 
+af_xdp_pool_debugfs_init();
+
 pr_info("af_xdp_pool: registered (skeleton, all callbacks stubbed -EOPNOTSUPP)\n");
 return 0;
 }
 
 static void __exit af_xdp_pool_exit(void)
 {
+af_xdp_pool_debugfs_exit();
 dpaa_unregister_flavor_ops();
 pr_info("af_xdp_pool: unregistered\n");
 }
